//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: found `i64`
//
// `type Age = i64` must not change how `i64` prints in a diagnostic that has nothing to
// do with `Age`.
//
// Types are hash-consed, so the alias and the primitive are one `TyId`; `Env::record_name`
// recorded the name against it and `print::def_name` reverse-maps an id to a name. Every
// `i64` in the whole compilation then printed as `Age` — this file reported "expected
// `str`, found `Age`" for the literal `3`. A name is only worth recording when it saves
// the printer from expanding something, and a primitive has nothing to expand.

use std::io;

type Age = i64

fn f(x: str) -> str { x }

fn main() {
    io::println(f(3));
}
